Personas. Each persona is a behavioral profile specifying which
action features trigger approval or denial: a Cautious developer denies API and schema changes and reviews carefully; a Permissive developer approves broadly and intervenes only on security-sensitive
changes; a Mixed developer approves tests and documentation
freely but denies large multi-file diffs. These three were chosen
to span the trust postures observed in our formative survey—one
risk-averse, one risk-tolerant, and one selective.
Features and units. The four features in Table 2 are:
(1) change_pattern_risk, a risk score derived from the type
of change (API and schema modifications score high, documentation and tests score low).
(2) model_confidence_avg, the model’s self-reported confidence
in the proposed action.
(3) is_security_sensitive, a binary flag for actions touching
security-related paths.
(4) prior_denials, tallying previous denials on similar actions.
Each cell in Table 2 reports Δ = learned − prior, the unitless
shift in the classifier’s logistic regression coefficient on that feature
relative to its warm-start value. Positive Δ means the feature now
pushes more strongly toward auto-approval; negative Δ pushes
toward a check-in.
